WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.268 --> 00:00:03.447
Viewers like you make
this program possible.

2
00:00:03.471 --> 00:00:05.339
Support your local PBS station.

3
00:00:32.500 --> 00:00:33.777
<i>How's he doing?</i>

4
00:00:33.801 --> 00:00:37.438
<i>He's fine.
At least he says he's fine.</i>

5
00:00:39.306 --> 00:00:41.084
<i>But is he just saying it.</i>

6
00:00:41.108 --> 00:00:43.320
<i>or does he really mean it?</i>

7
00:00:43.344 --> 00:00:46.280
<i>Truthfully.
I think he's just saying it.</i>

8
00:00:47.047 --> 00:00:48.592
He's tidying. Geordie.

9
00:00:48.616 --> 00:00:50.627
Since when does he tidy?

10
00:00:50.651 --> 00:00:52.295
Since five o'clock
this morning. apparently.

11
00:00:52.319 --> 00:00:55.565
-He's like a man possessed.
-He's not fine.

12
00:00:55.589 --> 00:00:57.792
No.
I don't think he's fine at all.

13
00:01:00.461 --> 00:01:04.064
{\an8}-Has his mother been in touch?
-Nothing. Radio silence.

14
00:01:04.665 --> 00:01:06.143
{\an8}Poor lad.

15
00:01:06.167 --> 00:01:08.678
{\an8}Must feel like she's abandoned
him all over again.

16
00:01:08.702 --> 00:01:09.746
{\an8}Who's abandoned who?

17
00:01:09.770 --> 00:01:12.373
{\an8}-Uh. Mrs C.
-And Dickens.

18
00:01:13.674 --> 00:01:15.719
{\an8}-Mrs C's abandoned Dickens?
-Yep.

19
00:01:15.743 --> 00:01:17.211
{\an8}That's about the size of it.

20
00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:21.725
{\an8}Why are you both in my kitchen?

21
00:01:21.749 --> 00:01:24.518
{\an8}I just wanted to see
if you'd spoken to the bishop.

22
00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:28.060
{\an8}You said you were going
to speak to the bishop.

23
00:01:28.522 --> 00:01:30.267
{\an8}Uh. yes.

24
00:01:30.291 --> 00:01:31.601
{\an8}With regard to me lay preaching.

25
00:01:31.625 --> 00:01:33.570
Yeah. I will. I will do that.

26
00:01:33.594 --> 00:01:35.372
You want to rejoin the church?

27
00:01:35.396 --> 00:01:36.756
I'm searching
for spiritual intent.

28
00:01:38.532 --> 00:01:39.867
I'm just here for the bacon.

29
00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:41.802
Ow.

30
00:01:43.204 --> 00:01:46.383
I'm seeing him next week.
I'll talk to him then.

31
00:01:46.407 --> 00:01:49.453
That would be marvellous.

32
00:01:49.477 --> 00:01:53.147
{\an8}Sooner rather than later.
if you could.

33
00:01:53.681 --> 00:01:54.682
{\an8}You busy?

34
00:01:55.449 --> 00:01:56.860
{\an8}I'm tidying. Geordie.

35
00:01:56.884 --> 00:01:58.886
{\an8}So I hear. Lord Worley...

36
00:02:03.891 --> 00:02:05.392
Not died. has he?

37
00:02:06.894 --> 00:02:08.371
Not that I know of.

38
00:02:08.395 --> 00:02:09.539
Why. is it on the cards?

39
00:02:09.563 --> 00:02:12.166
Well. uh...
He's old. He's lonely.

40
00:02:13.501 --> 00:02:14.711
Well. he's not got long left.

41
00:02:14.735 --> 00:02:16.480
I've been going up
to pray with him.

42
00:02:16.504 --> 00:02:18.281
That'll certainly
speed him along.

43
00:02:18.305 --> 00:02:19.616
No. he's been burgled.

44
00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:23.153
And I thought you could do
with a break from the tidying.

45
00:02:23.177 --> 00:02:24.278
Oh.

46
00:02:25.646 --> 00:02:27.348
Yeah. give me five minutes.

47
00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:34.255
Dickens?

48
00:02:35.656 --> 00:02:37.591
I panicked. Sorry.

49
00:02:56.877 --> 00:02:57.878
So...

50
00:02:58.946 --> 00:03:00.590
I'm fine.

51
00:03:00.614 --> 00:03:02.859
I haven't asked
you anything yet.

52
00:03:02.883 --> 00:03:04.952
You were going
to ask how I was doing.

53
00:03:05.185 --> 00:03:06.420
and the answer is "fine."

54
00:03:07.855 --> 00:03:10.190
Me and Meg were always
destined to be friends.

55
00:03:10.758 --> 00:03:11.759
You and Meg?

56
00:03:14.228 --> 00:03:15.696
What's happened
with you and Meg?

57
00:03:16.664 --> 00:03:17.707
Well. she's seeing someone else.

58
00:03:17.731 --> 00:03:19.400
which feels
like the right thing.

59
00:03:24.772 --> 00:03:26.716
Morning. Reuben. How are you?

60
00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:28.552
Briggs won't let
you in that way.

61
00:03:28.576 --> 00:03:29.577
You know how he gets.

62
00:03:30.444 --> 00:03:32.656
Ah.

63
00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:34.481
Geordie. I usually
go in through the kitchens.

64
00:03:35.215 --> 00:03:36.250
Buggar that.

65
00:03:39.353 --> 00:03:41.865
I wasn't thinking about Meg.
as it happens.

66
00:03:41.889 --> 00:03:43.900
I was thinking
about your mother.

67
00:03:43.924 --> 00:03:47.494
-Oh. that.
-Yeah. that.

68
00:03:50.898 --> 00:03:53.343
The way I see it.
God has a plan for me.

69
00:03:53.367 --> 00:03:56.246
And. well. my mother
being around at the moment.

70
00:03:56.270 --> 00:03:58.281
it isn't part of it. so...

71
00:03:58.305 --> 00:04:00.850
-Oh. it's God's will?
-Exactly.

72
00:04:00.874 --> 00:04:03.777
Only it might not
just be God's will.

73
00:04:08.248 --> 00:04:09.650
-What did you do?
-Nothing.

74
00:04:12.853 --> 00:04:14.355
I just suggested...

75
00:04:15.456 --> 00:04:17.367
Suggested what?

76
00:04:17.391 --> 00:04:21.028
That Mira needed to be
100% sure that she wanted this.

77
00:04:22.630 --> 00:04:23.940
Right.

78
00:04:23.964 --> 00:04:26.634
"This" being a relationship
with her son?

79
00:04:27.501 --> 00:04:29.512
Well. yes. I was trying to help.

80
00:04:29.536 --> 00:04:30.580
So let me get this straight.

81
00:04:30.604 --> 00:04:33.641
You find my mother.
against my will.

82
00:04:35.009 --> 00:04:36.853
and then you send her away.
also against my will.

83
00:04:36.877 --> 00:04:37.988
I don't want
to see you get hurt.

84
00:04:38.012 --> 00:04:40.323
Like now. you mean?

85
00:04:40.347 --> 00:04:42.892
You said you were fine.

86
00:04:42.916 --> 00:04:45.662
I am fine.

87
00:04:45.686 --> 00:04:48.465
Inspector Keating.
Cambridgeshire Police.

88
00:04:48.489 --> 00:04:50.724
Tradesmen's entrance
is left and left again.

89
00:04:51.525 --> 00:04:52.936
We're not tradesmen.

90
00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:55.538
Well. you're not the sort of
people I let in the front door.

91
00:04:55.562 --> 00:04:56.730
Is that right?

92
00:05:07.041 --> 00:05:10.654
I had a report about a burglary.

93
00:05:10.678 --> 00:05:12.513
Uh. excuse me one moment.

94
00:05:17.785 --> 00:05:18.952
Are you angry with me?

95
00:05:20.354 --> 00:05:21.422
No.

96
00:05:22.890 --> 00:05:24.391
You can be angry if you want.

97
00:05:25.726 --> 00:05:27.537
Well.
that's very generous of you.

98
00:05:27.561 --> 00:05:28.638
Thank you. Geordie.

99
00:05:28.662 --> 00:05:29.906
What on earth are those?

100
00:05:29.930 --> 00:05:32.533
-I made them.
-With what?

101
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.345
Flour. bicarb...

102
00:05:35.369 --> 00:05:36.880
You don't even know
what bicarb is.

103
00:05:36.904 --> 00:05:39.349
Prefix bi. meaning double.

104
00:05:39.373 --> 00:05:42.519
carbonate. meaning... carbonate.

105
00:05:42.543 --> 00:05:44.854
-Are you drunk?
-No.

106
00:05:44.878 --> 00:05:47.657
First time for everything.
I suppose. Briggs.

107
00:05:47.681 --> 00:05:49.726
Tell Father we're here for tea.

108
00:05:49.750 --> 00:05:51.952
And park the car. would you?
There's a good chap.

109
00:05:54.755 --> 00:05:56.633
Well. how about this?

110
00:05:56.657 --> 00:06:00.503
Strangers a calling.
How thrilling.

111
00:06:00.527 --> 00:06:02.972
They've just arrived
to investigate the burglary.

112
00:06:02.996 --> 00:06:04.098
Thank you. Briggs.

113
00:06:06.633 --> 00:06:08.044
Inspector.

114
00:06:08.068 --> 00:06:10.080
And you must be our vicar.

115
00:06:10.104 --> 00:06:12.549
Father said you were
something of a novelty.

116
00:06:12.573 --> 00:06:14.517
I wonder what he meant by that?

117
00:06:14.541 --> 00:06:16.486
If you'd follow Walter
to the scene of the crime

118
00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:18.655
and do whatever it is you do.

119
00:06:18.679 --> 00:06:20.523
We'd appreciate it
if this matter

120
00:06:20.547 --> 00:06:21.991
were dealt with <i>promptement.</i>

121
00:06:22.015 --> 00:06:24.394
He can't speak French.
He's just showing off.

122
00:06:24.418 --> 00:06:26.062
And she didn't make those cakes.

123
00:06:26.086 --> 00:06:27.497
I'll make a note of that.

124
00:06:27.521 --> 00:06:29.032
I've listed everything
that was taken.

125
00:06:29.056 --> 00:06:32.435
Bugger took everything of value.
Mother's brooches. her tiara.

126
00:06:32.459 --> 00:06:34.037
butterfly necklace
Allegra's been coveting.

127
00:06:34.061 --> 00:06:36.106
It's of deep sentimental value.

128
00:06:36.130 --> 00:06:38.108
Funny how your sentimentality
seems to correlate

129
00:06:38.132 --> 00:06:39.709
directly to the ratio
of diamonds.

130
00:06:39.733 --> 00:06:41.945
We'll need paperwork
for the insurance claim.

131
00:06:41.969 --> 00:06:43.847
And I <i>can</i> speak French.
by the way.

132
00:06:43.871 --> 00:06:45.548
Fluently. as it happens.

133
00:06:45.572 --> 00:06:47.474
I'm sorry. You are?

134
00:06:49.810 --> 00:06:53.514
The honourable Jonathan Worley.
son and heir of Lord Worley.

135
00:06:55.582 --> 00:06:57.994
That was clever.
Didn't even see your mouth move.

136
00:06:58.018 --> 00:06:59.596
Can we speak to your father?

137
00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:00.764
Lord Worley is sleeping.

138
00:07:00.788 --> 00:07:02.599
He's unaware of any
of this nastiness.

139
00:07:02.623 --> 00:07:04.825
And I intend
to keep it that way.

140
00:07:08.562 --> 00:07:10.607
See them out when they're done.

141
00:07:10.631 --> 00:07:12.742
Apologies for my brother.

142
00:07:12.766 --> 00:07:14.811
He can be
terribly grand sometimes.

143
00:07:14.835 --> 00:07:16.436
-Dipso.
-Degenerate.

144
00:07:17.905 --> 00:07:20.016
He has a wife
who hates him and a son

145
00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:22.910
who looks nothing like him.
Make of that what you will.

146
00:07:23.544 --> 00:07:24.545
Allegra.

147
00:07:26.747 --> 00:07:29.759
I don't suppose you fancy
a little pick-me-up. do you?

148
00:07:29.783 --> 00:07:31.118
We're working.

149
00:07:32.219 --> 00:07:34.731
Yes. yes. go on.

150
00:07:34.755 --> 00:07:36.833
I knew you were a <i>compadre.</i>

151
00:07:36.857 --> 00:07:38.835
I could tell
the moment I saw you.

152
00:07:38.859 --> 00:07:41.061
Show them
to the drawing room. Briggs.

153
00:07:41.862 --> 00:07:43.096
Follow me. please.

154
00:07:45.933 --> 00:07:46.967
I'm not working.

155
00:08:25.205 --> 00:08:29.219
Chucked it through the window.
rifled through the drawers.

156
00:08:29.243 --> 00:08:31.521
Who throws a paperweight when
you're trying to rob a place?

157
00:08:31.545 --> 00:08:34.224
Hmm? Why not jimmy the lock?

158
00:08:34.248 --> 00:08:37.918
And who keeps their jewellery
in the odds and sods drawer?

159
00:08:39.686 --> 00:08:42.689
No one keeps anything of
importance in drawers like this.

160
00:08:45.225 --> 00:08:47.194
This is where you say
you think it's been staged.

161
00:08:47.995 --> 00:08:50.697
and I say. "inside job."

162
00:08:51.899 --> 00:08:52.933
I put money on it.

163
00:08:54.134 --> 00:08:55.235
Ah.

164
00:08:56.003 --> 00:08:57.146
Thank you.

165
00:08:57.170 --> 00:08:58.948
Sure I can't tempt you.
Inspector?

166
00:08:58.972 --> 00:09:01.584
-Pretty sure.
-What shall we toast to?

167
00:09:01.608 --> 00:09:03.076
Another day. another bender.

168
00:09:03.844 --> 00:09:05.312
No retreat. no surrender.

169
00:09:07.648 --> 00:09:09.826
I think it's time
I spoke to Lord Worley.

170
00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:12.729
Jonty wouldn't like that.
And besides. Pa's...

171
00:09:12.753 --> 00:09:16.757
Sleeping? Here's a novel idea.
How about we wake him up?

172
00:09:17.724 --> 00:09:21.328
I object to this
with some gusto.

173
00:09:21.561 --> 00:09:23.973
Pa's very grumpy
when he's woken up.

174
00:09:23.997 --> 00:09:25.842
I think we can manage.

175
00:09:25.866 --> 00:09:27.033
Ready for round two. Vicar?

176
00:09:29.202 --> 00:09:30.971
Hmm. Why not?

177
00:09:34.808 --> 00:09:36.276
I could give you a few reasons.

178
00:09:43.717 --> 00:09:46.162
His Lordship's taking a nap.

179
00:09:46.186 --> 00:09:48.355
So everyone seems
very keen to tell me.

180
00:09:48.588 --> 00:09:49.966
Well. I've only
just got him off.

181
00:09:49.990 --> 00:09:51.334
so I'd rather
you didn't wake him.

182
00:09:51.358 --> 00:09:52.869
if it's all the same to you.

183
00:09:52.893 --> 00:09:55.171
And I'd rather you didn't
hamper my investigation.

184
00:09:55.195 --> 00:09:56.330
if it's all the same to you.

185
00:10:48.415 --> 00:10:49.892
<i>Go forth from this world</i>

186
00:10:49.916 --> 00:10:51.852
<i>in the love of God
who created you.</i>

187
00:10:57.290 --> 00:11:00.961
In the power of the Holy Spirit
who strengthens you.

188
00:11:03.663 --> 00:11:05.399
May you dwell this day in peace.

189
00:11:07.167 --> 00:11:08.235
It's your dream.

190
00:11:09.836 --> 00:11:11.738
It's the words from your dream.

191
00:11:12.406 --> 00:11:13.807
It's a prayer. Geordie.

192
00:11:25.185 --> 00:11:27.220
-<i>Silas Marner.</i>
-Never read it.

193
00:11:29.689 --> 00:11:31.291
It's about loneliness.

194
00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:35.729
Burn marks around his mouth.

195
00:11:36.463 --> 00:11:38.441
Poisoning.

196
00:11:38.465 --> 00:11:41.444
-My bet's on morphine.
-Very good. Larry.

197
00:11:41.468 --> 00:11:42.936
Mine too.

198
00:11:48.341 --> 00:11:49.810
He's been here hours.

199
00:11:54.781 --> 00:11:56.959
-If not days.
-How did they not notice?

200
00:11:56.983 --> 00:11:58.151
They noticed.

201
00:12:00.187 --> 00:12:01.388
Someone noticed.

202
00:12:03.457 --> 00:12:04.858
Give me a moment.

203
00:12:38.358 --> 00:12:40.369
How often did
you look in on Lord Worley?

204
00:12:40.393 --> 00:12:42.438
Every two hours.

205
00:12:42.462 --> 00:12:47.243
That's what his kids pay me for.
Badly. if truth be told.

206
00:12:47.267 --> 00:12:49.202
So you checked on him
two hours ago?

207
00:12:50.403 --> 00:12:51.938
He was asleep.

208
00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:55.251
What training do you have.
Hepsibah?

209
00:12:55.275 --> 00:12:58.387
Three years of nursing college.
five years on the job.

210
00:12:58.411 --> 00:12:59.956
Then I'm guessing
you know the difference

211
00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:04.827
between a man who's asleep
and one who's decomposing.

212
00:13:04.851 --> 00:13:07.196
I'm gonna lose my job
over this. aren't I?

213
00:13:07.220 --> 00:13:08.922
That's the least
of your worries. love.

214
00:13:10.891 --> 00:13:12.502
We come here once a week.

215
00:13:12.526 --> 00:13:14.036
Every Friday morning.

216
00:13:14.060 --> 00:13:17.807
-We have tea and cakes.
-And some terribly stilted chat.

217
00:13:17.831 --> 00:13:20.076
You were here last Friday?

218
00:13:20.100 --> 00:13:22.478
We couldn't do last Friday.

219
00:13:22.502 --> 00:13:25.348
-So. before that?
-Hard to pinpoint exactly.

220
00:13:25.372 --> 00:13:28.184
-A month or two back.
-Once in a blue moon. then?

221
00:13:28.208 --> 00:13:29.986
He was not an easy man.

222
00:13:30.010 --> 00:13:32.078
He was a bastard. Allegra.
Let's not be coy.

223
00:13:36.449 --> 00:13:38.051
He made our lives a misery.

224
00:13:40.053 --> 00:13:41.230
So the only people in the house

225
00:13:41.254 --> 00:13:42.865
for the past couple
of days would be...

226
00:13:42.889 --> 00:13:44.591
The nurse. and Briggs.

227
00:13:47.527 --> 00:13:49.496
-Larry. bring them both in.
-Boss.

228
00:13:54.568 --> 00:13:56.503
Thank you. sir.
We'll be in touch.

229
00:13:58.071 --> 00:13:59.239
My Lord.

230
00:14:02.142 --> 00:14:03.476
I'm Lord Worley now.

231
00:14:08.882 --> 00:14:09.983
My Lord...

232
00:14:14.287 --> 00:14:16.065
Jonty is buggering off.

233
00:14:16.089 --> 00:14:18.534
Business
to attend to. apparently.

234
00:14:18.558 --> 00:14:20.536
I can't stand the thought
of rattling around.

235
00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:21.962
just me and the ghosts.

236
00:14:23.330 --> 00:14:26.175
Stay for a little bit.
would you?

237
00:14:26.199 --> 00:14:27.199
You coming?

238
00:14:34.474 --> 00:14:36.543
She's just lost her father.
I should...

239
00:14:39.879 --> 00:14:41.014
Okey dokey.

240
00:14:55.929 --> 00:14:58.007
There's a bell pull
by Lord Worley's bed.

241
00:14:58.031 --> 00:15:00.667
It broke 10 years ago or more.

242
00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:02.378
like everything else
in the house.

243
00:15:02.402 --> 00:15:04.647
So. how did he get
your attention?

244
00:15:04.671 --> 00:15:06.382
I'd go and check on him.

245
00:15:06.406 --> 00:15:08.417
Mmm-hmm. How often?

246
00:15:08.441 --> 00:15:10.677
Morning. night...

247
00:15:11.645 --> 00:15:13.022
Often as I could.

248
00:15:13.046 --> 00:15:15.024
This morning. last night?

249
00:15:15.048 --> 00:15:17.260
I assumed the nurse was there.

250
00:15:17.284 --> 00:15:20.186
I assumed she was doing her job.

251
00:15:22.422 --> 00:15:24.600
And was she doing a good job.
in your opinion?

252
00:15:24.624 --> 00:15:26.168
No.

253
00:15:26.192 --> 00:15:29.639
-Negligent?
-It looked that way to me.

254
00:15:29.663 --> 00:15:33.276
But when you have two
rotten kids like Lord Worley.

255
00:15:33.300 --> 00:15:35.702
negligence is a lot better
than what he was used to.

256
00:15:35.935 --> 00:15:38.948
They said they were there
a month or so back.

257
00:15:38.972 --> 00:15:41.074
They haven't
visited him this year.

258
00:15:48.515 --> 00:15:52.686
Father expressly said never
to drink this. Are you game?

259
00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:55.264
I am if you are.

260
00:15:55.288 --> 00:15:57.324
Can hardly take it with him.

261
00:15:59.025 --> 00:16:02.071
He looks very pensive.

262
00:16:02.095 --> 00:16:05.565
Blotto. more like.
Runs in the family.

263
00:16:07.534 --> 00:16:08.577
Who is he?

264
00:16:08.601 --> 00:16:11.347
Oh. God. I don't know. Um...

265
00:16:11.371 --> 00:16:13.573
Great-great uncle
or some such...

266
00:16:15.208 --> 00:16:17.453
Amazing.

267
00:16:17.477 --> 00:16:19.322
That you can trace
your family all that way back.

268
00:16:19.346 --> 00:16:22.158
But you said
things would change...

269
00:16:22.182 --> 00:16:24.560
My father has just died.
How dare you.

270
00:16:24.584 --> 00:16:26.696
Ungrateful and insensitive.

271
00:16:26.720 --> 00:16:28.188
Be careful
you don't cross a line.

272
00:16:30.323 --> 00:16:36.172
This house is one
great big draughty mausoleum.

273
00:16:36.196 --> 00:16:38.765
Do you know the worst of it?
I don't get a bean.

274
00:16:38.998 --> 00:16:40.300
All goes to Jonts.

275
00:16:41.768 --> 00:16:44.571
Hmm. Praise be
to the firstborn boy.

276
00:16:45.638 --> 00:16:47.306
Praise be. indeed.

277
00:16:49.109 --> 00:16:51.153
She's from
a private nursing agency.

278
00:16:51.177 --> 00:16:52.212
Hired by the son.

279
00:16:53.680 --> 00:16:55.057
How long's she been
Lord Worley's...

280
00:16:55.081 --> 00:16:57.159
January 14 this year.
she started.

281
00:16:57.183 --> 00:16:58.694
No criminal record.

282
00:16:58.718 --> 00:17:01.397
Won an award
for compassion in 1961.

283
00:17:01.421 --> 00:17:04.100
What have you been
putting in his porridge?

284
00:17:04.124 --> 00:17:05.568
Personal development.

285
00:17:05.592 --> 00:17:07.303
My bedtime reading.

286
00:17:07.327 --> 00:17:09.038
I'm learning
to believe in myself.

287
00:17:09.062 --> 00:17:12.108
Mmm. Sounds a bit
too upbeat for my liking.

288
00:17:12.132 --> 00:17:13.400
You're reading it next.

289
00:17:18.171 --> 00:17:21.150
Uh. Miss Scott here
is gonna search your handbag

290
00:17:21.174 --> 00:17:23.786
because I've learned only
bad things happen when I do.

291
00:17:23.810 --> 00:17:24.811
If you must.

292
00:17:34.154 --> 00:17:37.457
Trip to Brighton.
Very nice. Bit of sea air.

293
00:17:41.094 --> 00:17:44.306
{\an8}Cinema yesterday at 08:30.

294
00:17:44.330 --> 00:17:45.641
{\an8}<i>Breath of Life.</i>

295
00:17:45.665 --> 00:17:47.367
There's irony for you.

296
00:17:49.536 --> 00:17:51.380
I don't expect
you to understand.

297
00:17:51.404 --> 00:17:53.182
Try me.

298
00:17:53.206 --> 00:17:57.453
This job.
all I see is suffering.

299
00:17:57.477 --> 00:18:01.424
Old folk dying alone
and no one to hold their hand.

300
00:18:01.448 --> 00:18:04.827
Apart from you. of course.
if you'd been there.

301
00:18:04.851 --> 00:18:09.422
It was just so...
airless in that room.

302
00:18:10.123 --> 00:18:11.567
So miserable.

303
00:18:11.591 --> 00:18:15.304
So you left him on his own

304
00:18:15.328 --> 00:18:17.706
for a day trip to the seaside?

305
00:18:17.730 --> 00:18:20.109
I feel awful. I do.

306
00:18:20.133 --> 00:18:22.445
He was a nice old chap.

307
00:18:22.469 --> 00:18:24.871
-A bit grumpy...
-Aren't we all?

308
00:18:26.606 --> 00:18:29.175
Sometimes it's all
just too much.

309
00:18:30.109 --> 00:18:32.488
You have to get away from it.

310
00:18:32.512 --> 00:18:35.825
All the death. all that sadness.

311
00:18:35.849 --> 00:18:38.184
-It's...
-Exhausting?

312
00:18:39.285 --> 00:18:41.497
He was a miser. Lord Worley.

313
00:18:41.521 --> 00:18:44.633
He made a note of every penny
that went into that house.

314
00:18:44.657 --> 00:18:46.159
every penny that came out.

315
00:18:46.759 --> 00:18:48.228
Every phone call.

316
00:18:48.795 --> 00:18:50.172
And where did he do that?

317
00:18:50.196 --> 00:18:51.364
In that book of his.

318
00:18:52.232 --> 00:18:54.477
The one about the old fella.

319
00:18:54.501 --> 00:18:57.313
<i>-Silas Marner?</i>
-That's the one.

320
00:18:57.337 --> 00:19:01.207
Wouldn't even stretch
to a notebook. old skinflint.

321
00:19:04.210 --> 00:19:06.145
Ring-ring. ring-ring.

322
00:19:06.880 --> 00:19:09.358
Reverend Finch speaking?

323
00:19:09.382 --> 00:19:11.393
How may I be of service
to you in this.

324
00:19:11.417 --> 00:19:14.853
your hour of desperate need?

325
00:19:16.456 --> 00:19:18.434
I can make believe. can't I?

326
00:19:18.458 --> 00:19:21.594
-Alphy?
-He's not here. He's...

327
00:19:22.629 --> 00:19:23.830
He's up at Lord Worley's.

328
00:19:24.531 --> 00:19:26.175
Not died. has he?

329
00:19:26.199 --> 00:19:28.477
Not that I know of. Will I do?

330
00:19:28.501 --> 00:19:30.212
-No.
-Oh.

331
00:19:30.236 --> 00:19:32.515
It's parish business.
and you are not of this parish.

332
00:19:32.539 --> 00:19:34.807
I am in my heart. Try me.

333
00:19:35.842 --> 00:19:38.821
A crime wave
is sweeping Grantchester.

334
00:19:38.845 --> 00:19:42.324
What is it? Barbarity? Bigamy?

335
00:19:42.348 --> 00:19:44.326
-Milk.
-Milk?

336
00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:46.729
Three bottles and a loaf
of granary bread.

337
00:19:46.753 --> 00:19:48.033
pinched right from the doorstep.

338
00:19:48.922 --> 00:19:51.190
This shall not stand. Mrs C.

339
00:19:52.191 --> 00:19:54.627
Mrs Green on Mill Road.

340
00:19:57.830 --> 00:19:59.808
She thought it was birds.

341
00:19:59.832 --> 00:20:02.745
Stealing a milk bottle
in its entirety?

342
00:20:02.769 --> 00:20:05.972
She's not quite the full ticket
anymore. bless her.

343
00:20:06.205 --> 00:20:09.485
-Ooh. I've had a thought.
-Oh. dear.

344
00:20:09.509 --> 00:20:11.787
Crime tends not to be random

345
00:20:11.811 --> 00:20:14.757
but influenced
by the intersection

346
00:20:14.781 --> 00:20:16.416
of offender and victim.

347
00:20:17.584 --> 00:20:19.395
Absolutely none the wiser.

348
00:20:19.419 --> 00:20:21.497
If we work out his pattern.

349
00:20:21.521 --> 00:20:24.466
we'll know where
he'll strike next.

350
00:20:24.490 --> 00:20:26.769
What was the next thing
that went missing?

351
00:20:26.793 --> 00:20:29.996
Pie from a window ledge
at Abbots Reach.

352
00:20:32.532 --> 00:20:34.434
Mr Brant's granary loaf.

353
00:20:35.702 --> 00:20:37.470
Milk from Lacie's farm.

354
00:20:45.745 --> 00:20:48.490
-There's no pattern.
-There is if you squint.

355
00:20:48.514 --> 00:20:50.583
He's gonna
strike again. Leonard.

356
00:20:51.651 --> 00:20:53.486
Then we must be ready for him.

357
00:20:59.926 --> 00:21:02.838
Okay. your turn.

358
00:21:02.862 --> 00:21:05.665
Tell me your deepest.
darkest secrets.

359
00:21:06.699 --> 00:21:09.478
Oh. I... I don't have any.

360
00:21:09.502 --> 00:21:12.505
Oh. come on. Every family
has a skeleton in their armoire.

361
00:21:13.573 --> 00:21:15.651
I don't really know my family.

362
00:21:15.675 --> 00:21:17.886
That is an outstanding skeleton.

363
00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:22.524
Also. I have no idea
what an armoire is.

364
00:21:22.548 --> 00:21:23.950
Tell me everything.

365
00:21:25.985 --> 00:21:27.453
Okay. um...

366
00:21:28.421 --> 00:21:29.589
Well. I was a foundling.

367
00:21:30.323 --> 00:21:31.467
Lucky bugger.

368
00:21:31.491 --> 00:21:33.493
I just met my mother. actually.

369
00:21:34.427 --> 00:21:35.704
Was she wicked?

370
00:21:35.728 --> 00:21:36.796
Mmm.

371
00:21:37.630 --> 00:21:38.974
She was lovely.

372
00:21:38.998 --> 00:21:39.998
Disappointing.

373
00:21:41.334 --> 00:21:42.511
Mmm.

374
00:21:42.535 --> 00:21:43.603
It just...

375
00:21:45.071 --> 00:21:47.040
It just didn't work out. and...

376
00:21:48.374 --> 00:21:49.575
Yeah. I'm okay with that.

377
00:21:54.947 --> 00:21:55.982
Hello?

378
00:22:20.406 --> 00:22:24.019
Yes. they are expensive.
but they're hand stitched.

379
00:22:24.043 --> 00:22:25.621
They're Italian.

380
00:22:25.645 --> 00:22:29.491
And I figure if we invest
in something more upmarket.

381
00:22:29.515 --> 00:22:31.760
then we get a more
upmarket customer.

382
00:22:31.784 --> 00:22:33.929
What's your instinct
telling you?

383
00:22:33.953 --> 00:22:35.564
We do it.

384
00:22:35.588 --> 00:22:37.700
Well. there you go then.

385
00:22:37.724 --> 00:22:40.102
Crikey.

386
00:22:40.126 --> 00:22:42.671
It sends me quite giddy.
making decisions.

387
00:22:42.695 --> 00:22:44.363
It shouldn't do.
You're bloody good at it.

388
00:22:44.964 --> 00:22:46.132
Am I?

389
00:22:46.365 --> 00:22:48.677
A bona fide woman of business.

390
00:22:48.701 --> 00:22:51.069
-Glamorous too.
-Tell that to my kids.

391
00:22:52.772 --> 00:22:54.450
<i>Hello. Cece's Boutique.</i>

392
00:22:54.474 --> 00:22:55.551
Are you still at it?

393
00:22:55.575 --> 00:22:57.019
Busy day.

394
00:22:57.043 --> 00:22:59.145
It's like
the Marie Celeste here.

395
00:22:59.378 --> 00:23:00.489
The kids are at Esme's.

396
00:23:00.513 --> 00:23:02.624
I thought we were
having a family dinner.

397
00:23:02.648 --> 00:23:03.950
<i>They are. just not with you.</i>

398
00:23:07.420 --> 00:23:09.098
Get some chips on your way home.
would you. love?

399
00:23:09.122 --> 00:23:11.467
Need more sustenance
than cream of tomato.

400
00:23:11.491 --> 00:23:12.801
Will do.

401
00:23:12.825 --> 00:23:14.665
-So. how was your day...
-<i>See you later. Bye.</i>

402
00:23:36.015 --> 00:23:37.750
{\an8}They never answered his calls.

403
00:23:40.186 --> 00:23:42.097
It's in a terrible shape.

404
00:23:42.121 --> 00:23:44.633
I suppose that's what
a lifetime of bad decisions

405
00:23:44.657 --> 00:23:47.160
-does to a place.
-Your father?

406
00:23:48.094 --> 00:23:50.773
Place was crumbling beneath him.

407
00:23:50.797 --> 00:23:53.876
You should have
seen it in its heyday.

408
00:23:53.900 --> 00:23:55.744
the parties we'd have.

409
00:23:55.768 --> 00:23:58.171
This room was filled
with the great and good.

410
00:23:59.472 --> 00:24:00.807
Band over here.

411
00:24:01.874 --> 00:24:04.677
Pa looking handsome
in his white tie.

412
00:24:05.778 --> 00:24:07.013
Mother. stunning.

413
00:24:08.447 --> 00:24:11.617
They'd dance for hours
until the sun came up.

414
00:24:44.750 --> 00:24:45.918
I loved Pa.

415
00:24:48.187 --> 00:24:51.257
And I despised him
at the same time.

416
00:24:51.490 --> 00:24:53.125
Is that a terrible
thing to admit?

417
00:24:54.961 --> 00:24:56.004
No.

418
00:24:56.028 --> 00:24:59.665
I grew up surrounded
by so many people.

419
00:25:00.933 --> 00:25:02.735
and I always felt so alone.

420
00:25:36.969 --> 00:25:39.772
I think it's time we got
another bottle. don't you?

421
00:25:58.958 --> 00:25:59.992
Alfy?

422
00:26:02.828 --> 00:26:03.896
Yeah?

423
00:26:08.167 --> 00:26:09.635
It's late. I should...

424
00:26:11.604 --> 00:26:13.005
Should you?

425
00:26:14.206 --> 00:26:15.808
I think so.

426
00:26:17.710 --> 00:26:18.778
That's a shame.

427
00:26:22.982 --> 00:26:24.016
Night.

428
00:26:27.887 --> 00:26:29.088
Please don't leave me.

429
00:26:53.679 --> 00:26:55.290
Ooh. Italian couture.

430
00:26:55.314 --> 00:26:56.992
Can you believe it?

431
00:26:57.016 --> 00:26:59.962
We'll have an actual Italian
in actual Italy

432
00:26:59.986 --> 00:27:02.264
making dresses
for little old Cece's.

433
00:27:02.288 --> 00:27:03.823
Am I going to die alone?

434
00:27:05.224 --> 00:27:07.803
And there was I. thinking
we were talking about me.

435
00:27:07.827 --> 00:27:09.395
Lord Worley's kids
left him to die.

436
00:27:10.296 --> 00:27:12.107
That's going to be me. isn't it?

437
00:27:12.131 --> 00:27:16.002
Aw. of course it isn't.
my darling.

438
00:27:16.802 --> 00:27:18.313
The men always go first.

439
00:27:18.337 --> 00:27:20.048
Probably only got
a few years left in you.

440
00:27:20.072 --> 00:27:22.217
-Cheers.
-Don't worry.

441
00:27:22.241 --> 00:27:24.353
I'll keep you in your dotage.

442
00:27:24.377 --> 00:27:26.712
Mr Switch says I'm a bona
fide businesswoman.

443
00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:30.320
Do you think I should take
the chief inspector job. Cath?

444
00:27:31.951 --> 00:27:35.130
I wouldn't be on the front line.
but maybe that's a good thing.

445
00:27:35.154 --> 00:27:37.032
I don't think I've got it
in me anymore.

446
00:27:37.056 --> 00:27:38.824
All that death. day after day.

447
00:27:40.226 --> 00:27:41.894
It's not even
the bodies. really.

448
00:27:42.795 --> 00:27:43.863
It's the people.

449
00:27:44.697 --> 00:27:46.298
It's their miserable lives.

450
00:27:47.833 --> 00:27:49.411
It drags you down in the end.

451
00:27:49.435 --> 00:27:51.070
-It sure does.
-Mmm.

452
00:27:53.973 --> 00:27:55.007
I'll see you later.

453
00:28:06.786 --> 00:28:09.155
Reuben. the gardener.

454
00:28:21.867 --> 00:28:23.412
Make it look more appealing.

455
00:28:23.436 --> 00:28:26.305
We're catching a thief.
Not winning the country show.

456
00:28:40.052 --> 00:28:41.053
Now what?

457
00:28:41.787 --> 00:28:42.888
We wait.

458
00:28:50.329 --> 00:28:51.397
Where's Alphy?

459
00:29:00.739 --> 00:29:02.619
Honestly? I have had it
up to the neck with you.

460
00:29:04.443 --> 00:29:05.883
And remember
who you're reporting to.

461
00:29:37.176 --> 00:29:38.344
Breakfast?

462
00:29:39.912 --> 00:29:42.047
I imagine you've worked up
quite an appetite.

463
00:29:42.815 --> 00:29:43.949
Um...

464
00:29:44.517 --> 00:29:46.461
No. thank you.

465
00:29:46.485 --> 00:29:47.953
Let me show you out. Vicar.

466
00:29:52.791 --> 00:29:56.138
-If you sell...
-When. When we sell...

467
00:29:56.162 --> 00:29:57.339
We'll be homeless. my Lord.

468
00:29:57.363 --> 00:29:58.507
Great.

469
00:29:58.531 --> 00:29:59.875
Do you think
you're the only one?

470
00:29:59.899 --> 00:30:02.968
I'm losing a home too.
So self-absorbed.

471
00:30:09.475 --> 00:30:12.020
Morning. Vicar.

472
00:30:12.044 --> 00:30:15.581
Good of you to minister to
my sister in her hour of need.

473
00:30:15.814 --> 00:30:17.850
Yeah.
you're selling. aren't you?

474
00:30:19.018 --> 00:30:21.320
Time to remove
the albatross from one's neck.

475
00:30:24.089 --> 00:30:26.368
Oh. good.
Your friend's here. too.

476
00:30:26.392 --> 00:30:27.903
Perfect.

477
00:30:27.927 --> 00:30:29.828
-Alphy.
-Alphy.

478
00:30:34.033 --> 00:30:35.601
You're up early.

479
00:30:35.834 --> 00:30:37.846
Yeah. I... I was just...

480
00:30:37.870 --> 00:30:40.115
Ah. Never complain.
never explain.

481
00:30:40.139 --> 00:30:41.850
Though I doubt he's got
much to complain about.

482
00:30:41.874 --> 00:30:43.251
My sister's quite a goer

483
00:30:43.275 --> 00:30:45.086
-by all accounts.
-Jonty.

484
00:30:45.110 --> 00:30:47.055
She collects conquests like
other people collects stamps.

485
00:30:47.079 --> 00:30:48.123
Don't you?

486
00:30:48.147 --> 00:30:50.358
And you're all purity
and light are you?

487
00:30:50.382 --> 00:30:53.028
She has a particular
fondness for the foreign ones.

488
00:30:53.052 --> 00:30:54.963
You're so vile.

489
00:30:54.987 --> 00:30:56.898
Always nice when
you've collected the whole set.

490
00:30:56.922 --> 00:30:57.923
isn't it. sis?

491
00:30:58.324 --> 00:30:59.358
Children.

492
00:31:00.492 --> 00:31:01.560
Enough.

493
00:31:03.596 --> 00:31:05.097
I'm looking for the gardener.

494
00:31:06.565 --> 00:31:08.276
According
to Lord Worley's records.

495
00:31:08.300 --> 00:31:11.046
he bought you
a paperweight for your birthday.

496
00:31:11.070 --> 00:31:12.104
The old bastard.

497
00:31:13.872 --> 00:31:16.384
Not a paperweight
kind of chap. I take it.

498
00:31:16.408 --> 00:31:18.911
I've dedicated
my life to this place.

499
00:31:19.478 --> 00:31:21.256
Like my father before me.

500
00:31:21.280 --> 00:31:25.594
Everything you see
right out here. that's my doing.

501
00:31:25.618 --> 00:31:27.229
And he gives me
a lousy paperweight.

502
00:31:27.253 --> 00:31:29.564
Which ended up
through his window.

503
00:31:29.588 --> 00:31:30.956
Yeah. I threw it.

504
00:31:32.024 --> 00:31:33.268
I'm not gonna deny it.

505
00:31:33.292 --> 00:31:34.536
Felt good to be honest with you.

506
00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:35.971
Well. you were angry.

507
00:31:35.995 --> 00:31:37.372
Yeah. I was angry.

508
00:31:37.396 --> 00:31:38.430
Angry enough to kill?

509
00:31:39.632 --> 00:31:41.109
What would I have
to gain from that?

510
00:31:41.133 --> 00:31:43.378
We live here. We got
a cottage on the estate.

511
00:31:43.402 --> 00:31:44.946
You're beholden to the family.

512
00:31:44.970 --> 00:31:46.147
Yeah.

513
00:31:46.171 --> 00:31:48.650
Me. my wife.
my little girl. Lily.

514
00:31:48.674 --> 00:31:50.285
We try and keep
on the right side of him.

515
00:31:50.309 --> 00:31:51.519
For all the good that's done.

516
00:31:51.543 --> 00:31:54.055
Where he's got
us living is damp.

517
00:31:54.079 --> 00:31:56.491
It's mouldy.
Lily is sick all the time.

518
00:31:56.515 --> 00:31:58.260
And I asked Lord Worley
to do something about it.

519
00:31:58.284 --> 00:32:00.095
-I begged him.
-Nothing?

520
00:32:00.119 --> 00:32:01.153
No. nothing.

521
00:32:02.321 --> 00:32:03.561
I saw you arguing with his son.

522
00:32:05.157 --> 00:32:07.626
Nah. Well. I hoped
he might care.

523
00:32:08.927 --> 00:32:10.329
but he's throwing us out. so.

524
00:32:17.069 --> 00:32:18.246
Just say what you want to say.

525
00:32:18.270 --> 00:32:19.438
I don't want to say anything.

526
00:32:20.673 --> 00:32:22.450
What the hell were you thinking?

527
00:32:22.474 --> 00:32:25.620
-There it is.
-Dallying with a suspect

528
00:32:25.644 --> 00:32:28.256
in the house of a dead man.
Her father. no less.

529
00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:29.491
Yeah. I...

530
00:32:29.515 --> 00:32:32.060
If you tell me you're fine
one more time.

531
00:32:32.084 --> 00:32:34.086
I will not be
responsible for my actions.

532
00:32:36.155 --> 00:32:37.666
I think I might be a bit lost.

533
00:32:37.690 --> 00:32:38.957
Lost?

534
00:32:40.359 --> 00:32:42.671
You're a Greek
flipping tragedy. Alphy.

535
00:32:42.695 --> 00:32:44.997
I'm not that bad.
I'm not saying you're bad.

536
00:32:47.032 --> 00:32:48.400
I'm saying the situation is...

537
00:32:50.703 --> 00:32:52.504
Your mother's
abandoned you again.

538
00:32:53.405 --> 00:32:54.983
And whose fault is that?

539
00:32:55.007 --> 00:32:56.475
She made a choice. Alphy.

540
00:32:58.210 --> 00:32:59.745
I didn't force her
to do anything.

541
00:33:00.512 --> 00:33:02.114
Just leave it. please.

542
00:33:10.556 --> 00:33:13.101
I saw something.

543
00:33:13.125 --> 00:33:16.128
In the house. Something I'm not
sure I was meant to see.

544
00:33:17.029 --> 00:33:18.063
You're telling me?

545
00:33:20.699 --> 00:33:22.701
Midway Auction House mean...

546
00:33:24.069 --> 00:33:25.204
Up by Jesus Green?

547
00:33:26.505 --> 00:33:29.441
Someone's boxing things up.
selling them off.

548
00:33:36.648 --> 00:33:40.028
I miss this. Being here.

549
00:33:40.052 --> 00:33:42.688
-You're here all the time.
-Not like when I was a curate.

550
00:33:43.722 --> 00:33:45.190
Do you ever feel
lacking in purpose?

551
00:33:45.591 --> 00:33:47.102
I'm a woman.

552
00:33:47.126 --> 00:33:49.161
All we have is purpose.
whether we like it or not.

553
00:33:50.396 --> 00:33:52.030
I wish I could come back.

554
00:33:53.399 --> 00:33:55.276
But you're doing so well.

555
00:33:55.300 --> 00:33:58.804
-You're helping men of sin.
-That's not what we call them.

556
00:33:59.037 --> 00:34:02.608
You're helping men who've made
bad decisions make good ones.

557
00:34:03.509 --> 00:34:05.787
It doesn't feel like God's work.

558
00:34:05.811 --> 00:34:07.455
He would approve. I'm sure.

559
00:34:07.479 --> 00:34:09.281
I like doing things for God.

560
00:34:10.382 --> 00:34:12.317
I'm drifting without the church.

561
00:34:13.085 --> 00:34:15.196
Like I don't have worth.

562
00:34:15.220 --> 00:34:18.390
You have worth. Leonard.
Silly boy.

563
00:34:21.727 --> 00:34:22.761
He's here.

564
00:34:25.130 --> 00:34:26.565
This is a citizen's arrest.

565
00:34:28.333 --> 00:34:29.401
Raymond?

566
00:34:32.671 --> 00:34:34.215
Go on. then.

567
00:34:34.239 --> 00:34:37.318
I'm mortally wounded. Mrs C.

568
00:34:37.342 --> 00:34:40.745
Raymond Hayes.
come back here right now!

569
00:35:10.409 --> 00:35:11.577
They don't look happy.

570
00:35:12.778 --> 00:35:14.756
Well. I doubt they know how.
to be honest.

571
00:35:14.780 --> 00:35:17.358
Well. this is gonna
push them over the edge.

572
00:35:17.382 --> 00:35:19.751
Looks like Daddy didn't
love them that much after all.

573
00:35:23.689 --> 00:35:26.568
Exhibit A. an empty plate.

574
00:35:26.592 --> 00:35:30.572
Once filled with some very good.
if rather crumbly. biscuits.

575
00:35:30.596 --> 00:35:32.207
They were meant to be crumbly.

576
00:35:32.231 --> 00:35:36.244
That wasn't a criticism. Mrs C.
Just an observation.

577
00:35:36.268 --> 00:35:38.203
What do you have to say
for yourself. young man?

578
00:35:39.738 --> 00:35:42.317
No. I bruise like a peach.

579
00:35:42.341 --> 00:35:44.686
Raymond. you come
right back here!

580
00:35:44.710 --> 00:35:47.312
Go on then.

581
00:35:52.384 --> 00:35:56.331
Midway Auctioneers.
Some nice stuff in here.

582
00:35:56.355 --> 00:35:58.600
Get yourself a real bargain.

583
00:35:58.624 --> 00:36:00.064
Why don't you stop
with the theatrics

584
00:36:00.158 --> 00:36:01.369
and tell us why we're here?

585
00:36:01.393 --> 00:36:02.837
There's no need
to be rude. Jonts.

586
00:36:02.861 --> 00:36:05.173
I'm not being rude.
I'm being to the point.

587
00:36:05.197 --> 00:36:06.474
Tomayto. tomahto.

588
00:36:06.498 --> 00:36:08.300
It's a fine collection
of jewellery.

589
00:36:08.934 --> 00:36:11.436
Tiara. brooches...

590
00:36:15.240 --> 00:36:16.451
Butterfly necklace.

591
00:36:16.475 --> 00:36:18.553
Some bastard stole them
and auctioned them off.

592
00:36:18.577 --> 00:36:20.388
Well. this catalogue
was from two months ago.

593
00:36:20.412 --> 00:36:22.624
Wrong.
These were the exact items

594
00:36:22.648 --> 00:36:24.192
stolen the day Father died.

595
00:36:24.216 --> 00:36:28.263
Only they'd already been stolen
and already been sold.

596
00:36:28.287 --> 00:36:29.655
By whom exactly?

597
00:36:33.926 --> 00:36:36.638
-There was a burglary.
-There was no burglary.

598
00:36:36.662 --> 00:36:39.507
I beg to differ.
The window and the paperweight.

599
00:36:39.531 --> 00:36:40.808
Nothing to do with it.

600
00:36:40.832 --> 00:36:43.611
You used it as an opportunity
to cover your tracks.

601
00:36:43.635 --> 00:36:46.371
Yeah. throw a few things about.
make it look like a burglary.

602
00:36:47.906 --> 00:36:50.542
You had quite a racket going.
according to the auction house.

603
00:36:52.611 --> 00:36:54.756
You've been selling
things off for months.

604
00:36:54.780 --> 00:36:57.425
You unconscionable little cow.

605
00:36:57.449 --> 00:36:59.694
Moo. moo. moo. You sold things.

606
00:36:59.718 --> 00:37:00.895
You sold
Great Granny's portrait.

607
00:37:00.919 --> 00:37:02.463
To keep the lights on.

608
00:37:02.487 --> 00:37:04.532
You'd sell the bloody
lights if you could.

609
00:37:04.556 --> 00:37:05.833
Looks like you got there first.

610
00:37:05.857 --> 00:37:08.603
And where were you. Jonty?
Everything was mouldering.

611
00:37:08.627 --> 00:37:10.572
What did it matter
if I took a few things?

612
00:37:10.596 --> 00:37:12.907
I own the house.
I own its contents.

613
00:37:12.931 --> 00:37:13.999
Wrong.

614
00:37:14.232 --> 00:37:16.902
You don't own
the house or its contents.

615
00:37:18.637 --> 00:37:19.705
Eppie does.

616
00:37:22.941 --> 00:37:25.620
And who. pray tell. is Eppie?

617
00:37:25.644 --> 00:37:28.347
Lord Worley's last
will and testament.

618
00:37:29.414 --> 00:37:30.983
And the lucky recipient is...

619
00:37:32.851 --> 00:37:35.597
Ta-da... You.

620
00:37:35.621 --> 00:37:38.466
You're having me on.

621
00:37:38.490 --> 00:37:42.737
"All my worldly goods
I bequeath to Eppie."

622
00:37:42.761 --> 00:37:43.929
Short for Hephzibah.

623
00:37:45.464 --> 00:37:47.942
Well. I didn't know
he'd done that.

624
00:37:47.966 --> 00:37:51.446
So you didn't get him to sign
over everything to you.

625
00:37:51.470 --> 00:37:53.548
Then you make him
a nice cup of tea.

626
00:37:53.572 --> 00:37:56.008
Milk. sugar.

627
00:37:56.775 --> 00:37:59.554
-morphine.
-No.

628
00:37:59.578 --> 00:38:02.991
You could almost understand it
if you'd helped him on his way.

629
00:38:03.015 --> 00:38:06.394
I went to the cinema
to avoid seeing him suffer.

630
00:38:06.418 --> 00:38:07.996
Why would I do that
if I was happy

631
00:38:08.020 --> 00:38:09.554
to put him out of his misery?

632
00:38:13.325 --> 00:38:14.393
So...

633
00:38:16.328 --> 00:38:17.629
I get the house then. do I?

634
00:38:19.331 --> 00:38:20.565
Imagine all the dusting.

635
00:38:21.700 --> 00:38:23.311
I knew he never loved us.

636
00:38:23.335 --> 00:38:26.505
Don't take it to heart. Jonty.
He wasn't capable of it.

637
00:38:27.739 --> 00:38:31.076
Perhaps if you'd shown
him some love in return.

638
00:38:31.309 --> 00:38:33.712
And what do you know of love?
You were never loved.

639
00:38:35.380 --> 00:38:37.625
Don't speak to him like that.

640
00:38:37.649 --> 00:38:40.395
So you're arresting her?
This Eppie?

641
00:38:40.419 --> 00:38:41.729
I knew I didn't trust her.

642
00:38:41.753 --> 00:38:44.699
She's staying in custody
till we complete our inquiries.

643
00:38:44.723 --> 00:38:46.491
-Good.
-As are you both.

644
00:38:47.426 --> 00:38:50.405
That is indefensible.

645
00:38:50.429 --> 00:38:51.863
Quite defensible as it happens.

646
00:38:52.998 --> 00:38:53.998
My Lord.

647
00:39:01.873 --> 00:39:03.675
Try not to disturb anything.

648
00:39:07.913 --> 00:39:09.347
We're missing something...

649
00:39:18.023 --> 00:39:19.458
Hospital corners.

650
00:39:23.962 --> 00:39:25.464
Two cups of tea.

651
00:39:27.699 --> 00:39:28.767
The lamp.

652
00:39:29.801 --> 00:39:31.612
Someone lit it for him.

653
00:39:31.636 --> 00:39:33.414
Paraffin levels suggests
it had been burning

654
00:39:33.438 --> 00:39:35.550
approximately 11 hours
before the death.

655
00:39:35.574 --> 00:39:38.686
So not the nurse.
because she was in the cinema.

656
00:39:38.710 --> 00:39:41.813
Someone sits with him.
smoothes his blankets.

657
00:39:42.914 --> 00:39:45.426
gives him tea.
brings him flowers.

658
00:39:45.450 --> 00:39:46.618
Someone cares.

659
00:39:51.022 --> 00:39:53.501
-Where's the book?
<i>-Silas Marner?</i>

660
00:39:53.525 --> 00:39:54.760
I've gone through all of it.

661
00:39:56.394 --> 00:39:57.462
Eppie.

662
00:39:58.997 --> 00:40:02.534
It isn't short for Hephzibah.
It's the girl in the story.

663
00:40:03.635 --> 00:40:06.681
Yeah. an old man.
saved from his misery.

664
00:40:06.705 --> 00:40:08.473
reborn through
the love of a child.

665
00:40:11.910 --> 00:40:14.479
There's only one person
who cared for Lord Worley.

666
00:40:18.650 --> 00:40:22.120
Don't tell me...
The bloody butler did it.

667
00:40:29.861 --> 00:40:32.564
Raymond Hayes.
you open this door.

668
00:40:36.501 --> 00:40:37.612
Where's your father?

669
00:40:37.636 --> 00:40:39.437
I'm not leaving
till I speak to him.

670
00:40:53.218 --> 00:40:54.786
I think he might be dying.

671
00:41:00.725 --> 00:41:02.870
<i>I liked him.</i>

672
00:41:02.894 --> 00:41:07.008
I know not many did. but he had
a good heart underneath it all.

673
00:41:07.032 --> 00:41:08.876
You brought him flowers.

674
00:41:08.900 --> 00:41:11.145
You tucked him in.
you lit a night light.

675
00:41:11.169 --> 00:41:13.004
He was afraid of
the dark at the end.

676
00:41:13.772 --> 00:41:15.116
Afraid of being alone.

677
00:41:15.140 --> 00:41:16.174
You're Eppie.

678
00:41:17.175 --> 00:41:18.886
Aren't you?

679
00:41:18.910 --> 00:41:19.945
He called you Eppie.

680
00:41:21.179 --> 00:41:23.148
He said I reminded him
of that book of his.

681
00:41:24.015 --> 00:41:25.617
I never read it myself.

682
00:41:26.818 --> 00:41:28.887
He gave me that name.
and I humoured him.

683
00:41:30.522 --> 00:41:31.833
Lord Worley asked you to make

684
00:41:31.857 --> 00:41:34.602
two phone calls
the night he died.

685
00:41:34.626 --> 00:41:37.672
To his daughter and to his son.

686
00:41:37.696 --> 00:41:40.575
He's asking for you.
Please. Miss Allegra.

687
00:41:40.599 --> 00:41:42.267
<i>I simply
can't be at his beck and call.</i>

688
00:41:42.500 --> 00:41:44.745
<i>Briggs. Selfish old fool.</i>

689
00:41:44.769 --> 00:41:47.539
He was in pain.
and he was lonely.

690
00:41:48.506 --> 00:41:50.685
<i>He wanted to see them.</i>

691
00:41:50.709 --> 00:41:51.886
What did you tell Lord Worley?

692
00:41:51.910 --> 00:41:53.511
That they were on their way.

693
00:41:54.880 --> 00:41:56.824
I didn't want to break
his heart.

694
00:41:56.848 --> 00:41:58.860
His children say
he was a tyrant.

695
00:41:58.884 --> 00:42:04.565
He was difficult. but he was
fascinating and worldly.

696
00:42:04.589 --> 00:42:07.268
They never once tried to put
themselves in his shoes.

697
00:42:07.292 --> 00:42:10.562
They only ever wanted to see
things how they saw them.

698
00:42:11.263 --> 00:42:13.074
Selfish bastards.

699
00:42:13.098 --> 00:42:15.710
So you sat up with him.
waiting for them to arrive.

700
00:42:15.734 --> 00:42:18.035
knowing they never would.

701
00:42:34.853 --> 00:42:36.254
<i>You brought him his cup of tea.</i>

702
00:42:38.757 --> 00:42:41.059
<i>With a fatal dose
of morphine in it.</i>

703
00:42:42.661 --> 00:42:44.262
<i>I didn't want him
to suffer any more.</i>

704
00:42:46.831 --> 00:42:47.933
<i>And he never had to know...</i>

705
00:42:50.936 --> 00:42:52.804
<i>that he was entirely
alone in this world.</i>

706
00:42:55.006 --> 00:42:58.619
<i>Doesn't everyone
deserve a bit of kindness?</i>

707
00:42:58.643 --> 00:43:01.989
Doesn't everyone deserve a bit
of compassion now and then?

708
00:43:02.013 --> 00:43:04.625
That compassion
will get you a few years inside.

709
00:43:04.649 --> 00:43:08.329
Worth it. I think. for a friend.

710
00:43:08.353 --> 00:43:11.666
And you get the house too.
which is quite the billy bonus.

711
00:43:11.690 --> 00:43:12.757
That's not the will.

712
00:43:14.125 --> 00:43:15.827
That's not
the last one he wrote.

713
00:43:19.798 --> 00:43:22.310
Well. according
to the solicitors it is.

714
00:43:22.334 --> 00:43:24.178
He went to another solicitor.

715
00:43:24.202 --> 00:43:25.804
I didn't care about the house.

716
00:43:27.038 --> 00:43:30.141
Lord Worley found
a more fitting beneficiary.

717
00:43:32.210 --> 00:43:35.380
The will's in an envelope.
a brown envelope.

718
00:43:51.029 --> 00:43:52.940
I thought no one kept anything

719
00:43:52.964 --> 00:43:54.366
of importance
in a drawer as this.

720
00:43:55.367 --> 00:43:57.402
Always happy to be proven wrong.

721
00:44:11.082 --> 00:44:14.019
-Don't tell me it's the kids.
-Well. Christ on a bike.

722
00:44:40.245 --> 00:44:41.813
Welcome home.

723
00:44:48.686 --> 00:44:50.188
What do you think of this. eh?

724
00:44:52.057 --> 00:44:54.025
Isn't it beautiful?

725
00:45:01.166 --> 00:45:04.469
This cannot be legally binding.
I refuse to believe it.

726
00:45:04.702 --> 00:45:06.347
Yeah. I'd get going
if I were you.

727
00:45:06.371 --> 00:45:08.949
-You're trespassing.
-Alphy.

728
00:45:08.973 --> 00:45:11.185
You must see what
a dire spot this has left us in.

729
00:45:11.209 --> 00:45:12.720
We have nowhere.

730
00:45:12.744 --> 00:45:14.989
-We have no one.
-And whose fault is that?

731
00:45:15.013 --> 00:45:16.481
You're no fun when you're pious.

732
00:45:17.982 --> 00:45:19.422
Good luck with
your stamp collecting.

733
00:45:44.342 --> 00:45:45.886
What's this?

734
00:45:45.910 --> 00:45:48.823
A little bedtime read.
<i>The Power of Positive Thinking.</i>

735
00:45:48.847 --> 00:45:50.057
Huh?

736
00:45:50.081 --> 00:45:51.681
I know you've got
a big decision to make.

737
00:45:52.750 --> 00:45:53.818
Chapter 6.

738
00:45:56.020 --> 00:45:58.389
-How do you know that?
-I know everything.

739
00:46:00.158 --> 00:46:01.526
What if I make
the wrong decision?

740
00:46:01.759 --> 00:46:02.827
Chapter 7.

741
00:46:05.897 --> 00:46:08.109
Well done for today. Larry.

742
00:46:08.133 --> 00:46:10.478
You're a detective
inspector in the making.

743
00:46:10.502 --> 00:46:13.037
-You reckon?
-I can almost guarantee it.

744
00:46:17.375 --> 00:46:20.211
He wasn't up to no good. was he?

745
00:46:22.247 --> 00:46:24.249
He came to the vicarage
to ask for help.

746
00:46:25.150 --> 00:46:26.817
Sensible young chap.

747
00:46:29.154 --> 00:46:30.831
We'll have you
right as rain in no time.

748
00:46:30.855 --> 00:46:32.190
I'll get you some more water.

749
00:46:33.291 --> 00:46:34.993
Doctor's on his way. Marcus.

750
00:46:43.268 --> 00:46:44.402
Thank you. Vicar.

751
00:46:48.940 --> 00:46:49.974
You're welcome.

752
00:46:51.442 --> 00:46:53.354
<i>"Dear sir.".</i>

753
00:46:53.378 --> 00:46:57.525
<i>As you know. I consider this job
more than a vocation.</i>

754
00:46:57.549 --> 00:46:59.417
<i>I consider it my life's work.</i>

755
00:47:01.019 --> 00:47:04.064
<i>In truth. I'd be
lost without it.</i>

756
00:47:04.088 --> 00:47:07.201
<i>So if it's a choice between
a life drifting about at home.</i>

757
00:47:07.225 --> 00:47:09.403
<i>getting under the wife's feet.</i>

758
00:47:09.427 --> 00:47:12.597
<i>"or a life of purpose.
then I choose the latter."</i>

759
00:47:12.830 --> 00:47:13.831
Pub?

760
00:47:16.568 --> 00:47:18.603
Go on then. Mr. Switch. Why not?

761
00:47:18.836 --> 00:47:20.205
Peter. please.

762
00:47:24.976 --> 00:47:27.488
<i>"Taking a step
back will be hard.</i>

763
00:47:27.512 --> 00:47:29.480
<i>but I know the station
is in safe hands."</i>

764
00:47:32.083 --> 00:47:36.487
<i>"It would be my honour to accept
the role of Chief Inspector."</i>

765
00:48:07.652 --> 00:48:08.886
The place looks good.

766
00:48:11.923 --> 00:48:14.158
Very tidy.

767
00:48:16.094 --> 00:48:17.929
I think it might
have been a distraction.

768
00:48:18.663 --> 00:48:20.131
The tidying.

769
00:48:21.099 --> 00:48:22.333
I didn't like to say it.

770
00:48:29.574 --> 00:48:31.442
I don't think my mum
wants to see me again.

771
00:48:34.012 --> 00:48:35.680
I know.

772
00:48:35.913 --> 00:48:37.515
Maybe it's God's will.

773
00:48:38.082 --> 00:48:39.250
Maybe.

774
00:48:41.486 --> 00:48:43.521
Or maybe I'm just
using that as an excuse.

775
00:48:44.489 --> 00:48:45.556
Maybe.

776
00:48:50.395 --> 00:48:52.297
Do you know what
I'd do if I were you?

777
00:48:53.531 --> 00:48:56.701
I'd get in your car.
I'd go and see her.

778
00:48:56.934 --> 00:48:58.369
however painful it might be.

779
00:48:59.370 --> 00:49:02.182
I'd listen
when I wanted to shout.

780
00:49:02.206 --> 00:49:04.709
I'd forgive
when I wanted to punish.

781
00:49:06.644 --> 00:49:08.613
The thing is. Alphy.

782
00:49:10.214 --> 00:49:13.251
God has a will. but so do we.

783
00:49:14.419 --> 00:49:16.430
We have one life.

784
00:49:16.454 --> 00:49:20.958
What kind of life would that be
if we sat and did nothing?

785
00:49:23.161 --> 00:49:24.529
What if she doesn't want me?

786
00:49:27.398 --> 00:49:29.167
Then we'll be here
waiting for you.
